04673nam a22007095i 9780812295603DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122956037 a10.9783/97808122956032doi  a(DE-B1597)521522  a(OCoLC)1143797352  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE748.G689 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a328.73092aB2231 aBadger, Anthony J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAlbert Gore, Sr. :bA Political Life /cAnthony J. Badger. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b10 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Culture in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. From Possum Hollow to Capitol Hill -- t2. A Washington Education -- t3. “Think Some More and Vote for Gore” -- t4. The Infrastructure Senator from the Sunbelt -- t5. The Triumph of a Racial Moderate -- t6. Gore’s Liberal Hopes and the Kennedy Promise -- t7 Race and War: Albert Gore and Lyndon Johnson -- t8. The Struggle for a Conservative Majority -- t9. The Defeat of a Roman Senator -- tEpilogue -- tPrimary Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn chronicling the life and career of Albert Gore, Sr., historian Anthony J. Badger seeks not just to explore the successes and failures of an important political figure who spent more than three decades in the national eye—and whose son would become Vice President of the United States—but also to explain the dramatic changes in the South that led to national political realignment.Born on a small farm in the hills of Tennessee, Gore served in Congress from 1938 to 1970, first in the House of Representatives and then in the Senate. During that time, the United States became a global superpower and the South a two party desegregated region. Gore, whom Badger describes as a policy-oriented liberal, saw the federal government as the answer to the South's problems. He held a resilient faith, according to Badger, in the federal government to regulate wages and prices in World War II, to further social welfare through the New Deal and the Great Society, and to promote economic growth and transform the infrastructure of the South.Gore worked to make Tennessee the "atomic capital" of the nation and to protect the Tennessee Valley Authority, while at the same time cosponsoring legislation to create the national highway system. He was more cautious in his approach to civil rights; though bolder than his moderate Southern peers, he struggled to adjust to the shifting political ground of the 1960s. His career was defined by his relationship with Lyndon Johnson, whose Vietnam policies Gore bitterly opposed. The injection of Christian perspectives into the state's politics ultimately distanced Gore's worldview from that of his constituents. Altogether, Gore's political rise and fall, Badger argues, illuminates the significance of race, religion, and class in the creation of the modern South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLegislatorszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aAutobiography.  aBiography.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.40uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229560340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812295603423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812295603.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK